00:18:13,375 --> 00:18:16,378
%%  Haunted heart %% 

320
00:18:18,380 --> 00:18:21,884
%%  Tortured soul %% 

321
00:18:23,385 --> 00:18:25,387
%%  I don’t know %% 

322
00:18:25,387 --> 00:18:27,806
?
%%  Why it needs to be free ?

323
00:18:28,107 --> 00:18:30,692
%%  I don’t know %% 

324
00:18:30,692 --> 00:18:33,645
?
%%  Why it needs to be me ?

325
00:18:34,146 --> 00:18:36,148
[Baby crying]

326
00:18:40,119 --> 00:18:43,155
%%  Wounded pride %% 

327
00:18:44,656 --> 00:18:48,827
%%  Cuts so deep %% 

328
00:18:50,329 --> 00:18:51,830
%%  I don’t know %% 

329
00:18:51,830 --> 00:18:55,334
%% 
%%  How to make it all right

330
00:18:55,334 --> 00:18:57,336
%%  I don’t know %% 

331
00:18:57,336 --> 00:19:00,839
%%  How to make it
through the night %% 

332
00:19:03,509 --> 00:19:07,596
%% 
%%  Somebody throw me a line

333
00:19:07,596 --> 00:19:11,066
%%  ‘Cause I’m hanging by a thread %% 

334
00:19:11,066 --> 00:19:13,101
%%  Hanging by a thread %% 

335
00:19:13,569 --> 00:19:17,606
%% 
%%  And it’s,
it’s just a matter of time

336
00:19:17,606 --> 00:19:19,992
%%  Till it comes undone %% 

337
00:19:38,377 --> 00:19:40,345
[Police siren blaring]

338
00:19:48,387 --> 00:19:50,389
[Sighs]

339
00:19:53,892 --> 00:19:55,811
[Ring]

340
00:19:57,396 --> 00:19:59,898
[Ring]
Uhh.

341
00:19:59,898 --> 00:20:01,900
[Ring]
Ohh.

342
00:20:03,402 --> 00:20:05,404
[Ring]

343
00:20:06,905 --> 00:20:08,407
Yeah?

344
00:20:08,407 --> 00:20:09,908
LESTER: McDaniels,
have you lost your mind?

345
00:20:10,409 --> 00:20:12,411
I leave you a message
to get your keister
in here early,

346
00:20:12,411 --> 00:20:14,413
and not only
are you not here early,

347
00:20:14,413 --> 00:20:15,914
you’re not even here
on time again.

348
00:20:15,914 --> 00:20:17,916
If you’re not in my office
in 30 minutes--
Yeah.

349
00:20:17,916 --> 00:20:21,420
There’s a line a mile long
of people who want this job.

350
00:20:21,420 --> 00:20:23,922
McDaniels,
are you listening to me?

351
00:20:24,423 --> 00:20:26,225
McDaniels?

352
00:20:34,483 --> 00:20:35,984
[Knock on window]

353
00:20:36,485 --> 00:20:37,986
Sam!

354
00:20:37,986 --> 00:20:39,988
[Knocking continues]

355
00:20:42,991 --> 00:20:44,493
It’s about time.

356
00:20:44,493 --> 00:20:46,495
I’ve been waiting
for an hour.

357
00:20:47,496 --> 00:20:49,498
My grandpa told me
you were back.

358
00:20:49,498 --> 00:20:51,283
My mom wouldn’t let me
come over till later.

359
00:20:51,450 --> 00:20:53,535
I figured
this was later.

360
00:20:54,036 --> 00:20:54,953
Are you better?

361
00:20:55,337 --> 00:20:57,422
I’m working on it.

362
00:20:57,422 --> 00:20:59,424
Let me look at you.

363
00:21:01,343 --> 00:21:02,794
Hmm. You don’t
look so bad.

364
00:21:04,680 --> 00:21:06,181
I’m much better.

365
00:21:06,181 --> 00:21:08,183
I think I’m going
back to school even.

366
00:21:08,183 --> 00:21:09,685
Oh! Thank goodness.

367
00:21:09,685 --> 00:21:11,553
If I have to eat lunch
one more day

368
00:21:11,553 --> 00:21:13,055
with Ashley Turner,

369
00:21:13,055 --> 00:21:15,057
I’ll just die!
I mean, it’s horrible.

370
00:21:15,057 --> 00:21:16,525
She--She smells
like liverwurst.

371
00:21:16,892 --> 00:21:18,477
Ugh!
[Laughs]

372
00:21:18,477 --> 00:21:21,813
[Sighs] Well, here.
I got you this.

373
00:21:22,114 --> 00:21:24,700
Sweet! Thanks.

374
00:21:26,568 --> 00:21:28,070
MADDY: Ben, get up!

375
00:21:28,570 --> 00:21:30,072
Quick!
My mom’s coming.

376
00:21:34,576 --> 00:21:36,578
Hey, Tybo,
you’re awake.

377
00:21:37,079 --> 00:21:38,997
Yep, I’m awake.

378
00:21:39,331 --> 00:21:41,333
Just sitting here...
being awake.

379
00:21:41,717 --> 00:21:43,802
Oh. Is that a new hat?

380
00:21:43,802 --> 00:21:46,305
You mean this thing?
Mm-hm.

381
00:21:46,805 --> 00:21:48,674
Mom. So, uh--

382
00:21:48,974 --> 00:21:51,893
So, I’m going back to
school today. Right?

383
00:21:52,311 --> 00:21:53,395
[Sighs]

384
00:21:53,895 --> 00:21:55,397
You think
you’re up to it?

385
00:21:55,397 --> 00:21:57,349
I think so.
I don’t know.

386
00:21:57,733 --> 00:21:58,817
What do you think, Sam?

387
00:21:59,184 --> 00:22:00,268
[Laughs]

388
00:22:00,268 --> 00:22:02,187
I think he’s ready.

389
00:22:02,487 --> 00:22:04,573
Way to be
stealth, Sam!

390
00:22:04,573 --> 00:22:05,574
[Laughs]
Hi, Miss Maddy.

391
00:22:05,574 --> 00:22:07,075
Hi, sweetheart.
How are you?

392
00:22:07,075 --> 00:22:09,578
I’m fine. My grandpa
told me Tyler was back.

393
00:22:09,578 --> 00:22:11,079
Hmm. How is
your grandpa?

394
00:22:11,580 --> 00:22:12,581
He’s good.
Good.

395
00:22:12,581 --> 00:22:14,082
And grumpy.
[Laughs]

396
00:22:14,082 --> 00:22:15,584
Okay. Good
and grumpy, then.

397
00:22:16,084 --> 00:22:17,369
[Laughs]

398
00:22:17,619 --> 00:22:18,704
Well, I guess if you’re
going to school,

399
00:22:18,704 --> 00:22:20,038
you ought to start
getting ready.

400
00:22:20,288 --> 00:22:21,373
Yes!
Yes!

401
00:22:22,841 --> 00:22:24,876
Ah-ah-ah!
Front door, please.

402
00:22:24,876 --> 00:22:25,877
Sure, Miss Maddy.

403
00:22:25,877 --> 00:22:27,346
Thank you, young lady.

404
00:22:27,679 --> 00:22:29,264
See you on the bus, Ty.

405
00:22:29,264 --> 00:22:30,682
,
Oh, no. You know what?
I’ve got to check him in

406
00:22:30,966 --> 00:22:32,551
so he’ll
see you there later.

407
00:22:32,551 --> 00:22:34,052
Scoot!

408
00:22:38,190 --> 00:22:40,692
Oh, come on.
A walking route?

409
00:22:40,692 --> 00:22:43,195
Yes. You know, one foot
in front of the other,

410
00:22:43,195 --> 00:22:44,696
point A to point B,

411
00:22:44,696 --> 00:22:46,198
deliver the mail
in between.

412
00:22:46,198 --> 00:22:47,699
If it’s all the same
to you,

413
00:22:47,699 --> 00:22:49,201
I’d rather just keep
working the line.

414
00:22:49,201 --> 00:22:50,702
I can’t do
a walking route.

415
00:22:50,702 --> 00:22:52,704
Oh, you can
and you will.

416
00:22:53,205 --> 00:22:55,207
Uh, here’s the keys.

417
00:22:55,207 --> 00:22:58,710
The truck is in 27 outside,
loaded and ready.

418
00:22:58,710 --> 00:23:00,212
.
Here’s your line of travel

419
00:23:00,712 --> 00:23:02,714
Heh. Follow the mail,
and you can’t get lost.

420
00:23:02,714 --> 00:23:05,717
Nancy’s got
your uniform out back.

421
00:23:05,717 --> 00:23:08,220
You’re already
two hours behind,

422
00:23:08,220 --> 00:23:10,222
so I’d step on it.

423
00:23:17,095 --> 00:23:18,597
[Knock on door]

424
00:23:18,597 --> 00:23:20,098
Yeah.

425
00:23:22,100 --> 00:23:23,602
You ready?

426
00:23:23,602 --> 00:23:26,104
Mom?
Mm-hm?

427
00:23:26,104 --> 00:23:27,606
Do you think
the kids at school

428
00:23:28,106 --> 00:23:30,609
will make fun of me?

429
00:23:30,609 --> 00:23:32,077
Some will.

430
00:23:32,077 --> 00:23:35,113
Only because they don’t
know what else to say.

431
00:23:35,113 --> 00:23:37,115
Hmm.

432
00:23:37,616 --> 00:23:40,619
What should I do
if they do?

433
00:23:40,619 --> 00:23:43,121
Wait. I know.

434
00:23:43,121 --> 00:23:45,123
I’ll do what
Jesus would do.

435
00:23:46,625 --> 00:23:48,627
You don’t have to go,
you know.

436
00:23:48,627 --> 00:23:50,629
No. I have to go.

437
00:23:51,129 --> 00:23:53,131
Sam needs me.

438
00:23:53,131 --> 00:23:55,634
Ashley Turner
smells like liverwurst.

439
00:23:55,634 --> 00:23:57,135
[Laughs]

440
00:23:58,603 --> 00:24:00,138
Mmm.

441
00:24:00,639 --> 00:24:02,140
I am so proud
of you.

442
00:24:04,142 --> 00:24:07,562
Mmm! You’re gonna
have a great day.

443
00:24:25,881 --> 00:24:27,883
[Sighs]

444
00:24:29,384 --> 00:24:30,886
I’m in hell.

445
00:24:55,360 --> 00:24:56,361
[Growls]

446
00:24:56,661 --> 00:24:58,580
[Barking]

447
00:25:00,415 --> 00:25:02,834
Good dog. Right?

448
00:25:02,834 --> 00:25:03,835
Good dog.

449
00:25:04,252 --> 00:25:06,955
Stay. Stay! Stay!

450
00:25:06,955 --> 00:25:08,590
Uhh!

451
00:25:09,007 --> 00:25:11,376
[Growling]

452
00:25:11,376 --> 00:25:12,794
Let go!

453
00:25:13,094 --> 00:25:14,129
[Growling]

454
00:25:18,016 --> 00:25:19,885
[Barking]

455
00:25:25,307 --> 00:25:27,275
[Barking continues]

456
00:25:33,732 --> 00:25:35,817
[Barking continues]

457
00:25:41,790 --> 00:25:42,791
Ohh!

458
00:25:42,791 --> 00:25:44,292
[Sighs]

459
00:25:44,292 --> 00:25:47,295
Whew! Whew.

460
00:25:47,295 --> 00:25:48,797
[Barks]
Aah!

461
00:25:48,797 --> 00:25:51,499
Ohh! Okay.
Bad dog. Bad dog!

462
00:25:55,503 --> 00:25:56,388
Alex?

463
00:25:56,671 --> 00:25:58,256
Can I catch
his disease?

464
00:25:58,757 --> 00:26:01,059
You know, if he spits
on me or something?

465
00:26:01,226 --> 00:26:02,811
No, you knucklehead.

466
00:26:02,811 --> 00:26:04,763
He has cancer,
not cooties.

467
00:26:05,146 --> 00:26:07,682
Samantha, we don’t
call people names.

468
00:26:08,066 --> 00:26:10,518
No, Alex, cancer
is not contagious.

469
00:26:10,819 --> 00:26:12,904
And Tyler’s been
through a lot.

470
00:26:12,904 --> 00:26:14,906
He’s missed over
two months of school.

471
00:26:14,906 --> 00:26:17,826
He’s probably gonna be
a little scared at first,

472
00:26:17,826 --> 00:26:19,828
so let’s all welcome
him back to class

473
00:26:19,828 --> 00:26:21,329
with big smiles and hugs...

474
00:26:21,830 --> 00:26:23,782
and kind words, Alex?

475
00:26:24,199 --> 00:26:25,700
If that’s possible.

476
00:26:26,034 --> 00:26:27,118
Whatever.

477
00:26:27,619 --> 00:26:30,338
Okay. While we’re waiting
for him to get all signed in,

478
00:26:30,338 --> 00:26:32,340
everybody put away
your notebooks,

479
00:26:32,340 --> 00:26:33,792
and let’s get ready
for lunch.

480
00:26:35,760 --> 00:26:36,795
TEACHER:
Tyler, welcome back.

481
00:26:37,295 --> 00:26:38,964
KIDS: Hi, Tyler!

482
00:26:39,464 --> 00:26:41,266
Mrs. Doherty, we were
just getting ready

483
00:26:41,266 --> 00:26:42,717
to go to lunch.

484
00:26:42,717 --> 00:26:43,768
[School bell rings]

485
00:26:43,768 --> 00:26:46,021
Okay, class, line up.
Line leaders?

486
00:26:46,021 --> 00:26:48,023
Everybody, line up
behind Amy.

487
00:26:49,524 --> 00:26:51,977
We are so glad
to see Tyler.
Oh, thank you.

488
00:26:52,527 --> 00:26:54,029
Is there anything
I should look out for?

489
00:26:54,029 --> 00:26:55,530
Um, no.

490
00:26:55,530 --> 00:26:57,032
Oh, you know what?
He might get tired.

491
00:26:57,032 --> 00:26:58,533
If he does,
just call me.

492
00:26:58,533 --> 00:26:59,534
I’ll come right back
and pick him up.

493
00:27:00,035 --> 00:27:02,037
Okay. I’ll keep
an eye on him.
Thank you.

494
00:27:02,537 --> 00:27:04,122
Oh, oh,
you know what?

495
00:27:04,122 --> 00:27:05,624
He still has a central
medicine line,

496
00:27:05,624 --> 00:27:08,126
so just make sure
he doesn’t get
submerged in water.

497
00:27:08,627 --> 00:27:11,963
[Laughs]
Sorry, that’s silly.

498
00:27:12,213 --> 00:27:13,298
You can stay
if you’d like.

499
00:27:13,798 --> 00:27:15,300
No, no. No, I’m fine.
Thank you.

500
00:27:15,300 --> 00:27:17,168
Okay.

501
00:27:17,469 --> 00:27:19,504
[Overlapping chatter]

502
00:27:19,838 --> 00:27:21,423
Bye.

503
00:27:22,924 --> 00:27:23,925
He’ll be fine.

504
00:27:25,927 --> 00:27:27,429
He’ll be fine.

505
00:27:28,930 --> 00:27:30,932
[Kids chattering]

506
00:27:33,935 --> 00:27:35,937
TYLER: I’m going back
so they can give me
medicine from a bag

507
00:27:35,937 --> 00:27:37,439
for a few days
every month.

508
00:27:37,439 --> 00:27:39,441
BOY: How does that
make you feel?

509
00:27:39,441 --> 00:27:42,444
Makes me feel sick.
They do that for a while.

510
00:27:42,944 --> 00:27:45,413
Then I get my cells back,
and then I’m done.

511
00:27:45,780 --> 00:27:47,115
Did they
call you "Baldy"?

512
00:27:47,415 --> 00:27:49,451
Heh. Is that why you wear
that funny hat?

513
00:27:49,834 --> 00:27:52,253
I’m warning you, Alex.

514
00:27:52,537 --> 00:27:55,123
Whatever. I bet that
radiation stuff hurts, huh?

515
00:27:55,623 --> 00:27:57,125
Especially on
a little wimp like you.

516
00:27:57,125 --> 00:27:59,260
Nah. But they made me
lay real still,

517
00:27:59,761 --> 00:28:01,262
like,
for five minutes a day,

518
00:28:01,262 --> 00:28:03,682
while this big machine points
at my head and my back.

519
00:28:03,965 --> 00:28:05,517
That’s it?

520
00:28:05,517 --> 00:28:07,519
Is that it?
Is that it? No.

521
00:28:07,519 --> 00:28:09,521
There’s a big laser beam
, like in Star Wars,

522
00:28:10,021 --> 00:28:12,023
that shoots out and kills
all the cancer cells.

523
00:28:12,023 --> 00:28:13,024
Right, Ty?

524
00:28:13,391 --> 00:28:14,976
Well, yeah, I guess.

525
00:28:14,976 --> 00:28:17,028
Huh.
Told you.

526
00:28:17,028 --> 00:28:19,981
So...does that
make you sick?

527
00:28:20,365 --> 00:28:22,283
Not as sick as
your liverwurst makes me.

528
00:28:22,534 --> 00:28:24,119
[Chuckles]

529
00:28:24,119 --> 00:28:25,453
Well, not too sick.

530
00:28:25,704 --> 00:28:27,789
But I heard my doctor
tell my mom

531
00:28:27,789 --> 00:28:30,158
that I probably won’t grow 
like I’m supposed to
because of it.

532
00:28:30,492 --> 00:28:33,378
Heh. So, you’re gonna stay looking like an alien?

533
00:28:33,545 --> 00:28:35,463
That’s it!

534
00:28:37,999 --> 00:28:40,919
[Kids laughing]

535
00:28:43,838 --> 00:28:45,840
TYLER: "Dear God...

536
00:28:45,840 --> 00:28:49,344
"my first day back at school
was very exciting.

537
00:28:49,344 --> 00:28:52,764
"I forgot to tell Sam
to do what Jesus would do.

538
00:28:53,181 --> 00:28:55,266
"We all ended up
in the principal’s office

539
00:28:55,266 --> 00:28:57,268
to sort things out."

540
00:29:02,741 --> 00:29:05,160
"My mom came
for me and Sam.

541
00:29:05,443 --> 00:29:07,529
"I’m not sure who she was more worried about.

542
00:29:08,029 --> 00:29:11,249
"On the way home,
Mom tried to be very firm.

543
00:29:11,249 --> 00:29:13,251
"But when Sam told her
how mashed potatoes

544
00:29:13,251 --> 00:29:14,619
,
"were stuck up Alex’s nose

545
00:29:14,869 --> 00:29:17,455
"she laughed and laughed.

546
00:29:17,956 --> 00:29:20,792
"Now I know
You’re getting my letters.

547
00:29:20,792 --> 00:29:22,844
"Because only You could
figure out a way

548
00:29:22,844 --> 00:29:24,846
to make her laugh."

549
00:29:28,049 --> 00:29:32,137
"We got home just when
the mailman was at her house.

550
00:29:32,137 --> 00:29:34,139
"I guess all the excitement
got to me,

551
00:29:34,139 --> 00:29:35,640
because I threw up
on his shoes."

552
00:29:39,644 --> 00:29:41,729
"My mom
couldn’t believe it.

553
00:29:41,729 --> 00:29:43,731
All she could do
was laugh."

554
00:29:46,734 --> 00:29:48,236
"All in all, God,

555
00:29:48,236 --> 00:29:50,738
it was a very good day."

556
00:29:58,213 --> 00:29:59,214
Oh-ho-ho-ho.

557
00:29:59,714 --> 00:30:01,216
How was--
How was my day?

558
00:30:01,216 --> 00:30:02,717
Well, uh, let’s see.

559
00:30:02,717 --> 00:30:05,220
I almost got eaten
by a horse,

560
00:30:05,220 --> 00:30:07,722
and some old man tried
to chase me off his porch

561
00:30:07,722 --> 00:30:09,724
with a cane.

562
00:30:09,724 --> 00:30:11,726
Oh, and then a kid
barfed on my shoes.

563
00:30:11,726 --> 00:30:13,728
That’s what smells.

564
00:30:13,728 --> 00:30:16,731
Boss, we’ve already had
four complaints in one day,

565
00:30:16,731 --> 00:30:19,234
which is very good.
Might be a Post Office record.

566
00:30:19,234 --> 00:30:21,236
Four is not so bad.

567
00:30:21,236 --> 00:30:23,238
Oh, and one
possible lawsuit.

568
00:30:23,238 --> 00:30:26,241
Do you know a guy
by the name of
Cornelius Perryfield?

569
00:30:28,743 --> 00:30:30,245
God.

570
00:30:30,245 --> 00:30:31,663
Letters to God.

571
00:30:31,996 --> 00:30:34,082
These are from the kid
who threw up on my shoes.

572
00:30:34,082 --> 00:30:35,583
What am I supposed
to do with these?

573
00:30:35,583 --> 00:30:38,086
It’s your journey,
Brady. You decide.

574
00:30:38,086 --> 00:30:39,587
[Mouths]

575
00:30:39,587 --> 00:30:41,089
You know, if you’d
been here on time,

576
00:30:41,089 --> 00:30:43,091
there would’ve been
a dead letter bin
about right here.

577
00:30:43,091 --> 00:30:45,593
But since it’s
well after 6:00,

578
00:30:45,593 --> 00:30:47,595
they’ve moved that bin
over to the warehouse.

579
00:30:47,595 --> 00:30:49,597
So, you might want to just
gather your little letters

580
00:30:49,597 --> 00:30:51,599
and walk ‘em over.

581
00:30:53,101 --> 00:30:55,103
Thank you so much.

582
00:30:57,105 --> 00:30:58,389
[Clicks tongue]

583
00:31:00,225 --> 00:31:01,226
Ready!

584
00:31:04,195 --> 00:31:06,698
Ready, Jack. Ready.

585
00:31:06,698 --> 00:31:08,700
Isn’t that what you say-
- ready or steady?

586
00:31:09,200 --> 00:31:10,201
Well, I’m ready.

587
00:31:10,201 --> 00:31:11,703
Ah, I think you’ve
had enough.

588
00:31:13,204 --> 00:31:15,206
[Chuckles]

589
00:31:16,708 --> 00:31:17,709
All right.

590
00:31:17,709 --> 00:31:20,128
I’ll just take
my business elsewhere.

591
00:31:20,495 --> 00:31:22,580
You are a royal pain
anyway.

592
00:31:24,082 --> 00:31:25,583
Brady.

593
00:31:26,084 --> 00:31:27,585
Brady.

594
00:31:27,585 --> 00:31:30,088
Give me your keys,
I’ll pour you one more.

595
00:31:32,557 --> 00:31:35,560
I don’t see you taking
anyone else’s keys
around here.

596
00:31:35,977 --> 00:31:38,062
I don’t see anybody else
staggering around.

597
00:31:38,062 --> 00:31:39,564
You can stay
or you can go,

598
00:31:40,064 --> 00:31:41,566
.
but either way,
I’m gonna take your keys

599
00:31:51,359 --> 00:31:52,860
Hold these for a minute.

600
00:31:54,913 --> 00:31:56,414
What are these?

601
00:31:56,698 --> 00:31:58,583
Uh...

602
00:31:58,750 --> 00:32:00,335
some kid on my route.

603
00:32:00,335 --> 00:32:02,337
I don’t know what to do.

604
00:32:02,337 --> 00:32:04,839
How are you gonna
deliver these, man?

605
00:32:07,342 --> 00:32:10,345
Doesn’t seem right
to shred ‘em.

606
00:32:10,345 --> 00:32:11,846
I don’t know.

607
00:32:12,347 --> 00:32:13,848
Letters to God?

608
00:32:13,848 --> 00:32:17,852
Maybe you should
take ‘em to church
with you on Sunday.

609
00:32:19,103 --> 00:32:20,688
Yeah. Yeah, that’s--

610
00:32:21,189 --> 00:32:22,690
that’s what I’ll do.

611
00:34:18,840 --> 00:34:19,724
MAN: Can I help you?

612
00:34:20,058 --> 00:34:22,143
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

613
00:34:22,143 --> 00:34:24,062
A little warning next time.

614
00:34:25,930 --> 00:34:28,900
Sir. Mr. Reverend.
I mean--

615
00:34:28,900 --> 00:34:30,902
No. Please,
call me Andy.

616
00:34:30,902 --> 00:34:32,904
Andy, sure.

617
00:34:32,904 --> 00:34:34,405
And you are?

618
00:34:34,906 --> 00:34:37,408
Uh, Brady.

619
00:34:37,408 --> 00:34:39,861
And I was just
dropping those off.

620
00:34:39,861 --> 00:34:42,413
I wasn’t stealing
anything, I swear.

621
00:34:43,915 --> 00:34:47,418
I’m sorry. That’s a bad
choice of words.

622
00:34:47,418 --> 00:34:49,921
I just--
I just came in...

623
00:34:49,921 --> 00:34:52,924
.
just because--
it’s just that I think..

624
00:34:52,924 --> 00:34:55,927
this sick kid
on my route

625
00:34:55,927 --> 00:34:57,929
is writing these--

626
00:34:58,429 --> 00:35:01,933
these letters to...God.

627
00:35:01,933 --> 00:35:06,721
And I thought you could
at least read them,

628
00:35:06,721 --> 00:35:10,775
and send him, uh,
a gift basket or something.

629
00:35:11,058 --> 00:35:13,144
That’s very kind of you,
going out of your way

630
00:35:13,144 --> 00:35:16,397
to make sure that Tyler’
s letters are protected.

631
00:35:16,397 --> 00:35:17,398
You know him?

632
00:35:17,398 --> 00:35:20,401
Oh, yes. Yeah,
we love that family.

633
00:35:20,401 --> 00:35:22,403
They’ve been members
here for...

634
00:35:22,403 --> 00:35:23,821
quite a while.

635
00:35:24,155 --> 00:35:27,241
With all that’s
happened, it’s been...

636
00:35:27,241 --> 00:35:29,744
difficult for them.

637
00:35:29,744 --> 00:35:33,247
But we certainly
keep them in our prayers

638
00:35:33,748 --> 00:35:35,750
and check on them often.

639
00:35:39,754 --> 00:35:43,057
You know, it seems to me

640
00:35:43,057 --> 00:35:45,560
that God put these
letters in your hands

641
00:35:45,560 --> 00:35:47,562
for a reason.

642
00:35:47,562 --> 00:35:50,515
So, maybe you should
hold on to them.

643
00:35:50,515 --> 00:35:52,066
No, I wouldn’t--

644
00:35:52,066 --> 00:35:54,569
I don’t know what
to do with them. I, uh--

645
00:35:54,569 --> 00:35:56,571
Well, first thing
you’re gonna do

646
00:35:56,571 --> 00:35:59,073
is go home
and sleep it off.

647
00:35:59,073 --> 00:36:01,025
And then...

648
00:36:01,442 --> 00:36:03,528
listen to God.

649
00:36:05,029 --> 00:36:07,949
Let God tell you
what to do with them.

650
00:36:08,282 --> 00:36:10,368
After all, they are
written to Him.

651
00:36:14,872 --> 00:36:16,874
And you know you’re
always welcome here.

652
00:36:16,874 --> 00:36:19,377
This is a great place
to find answers.

653
00:36:21,879 --> 00:36:23,881
Hey, can I, uh--

654
00:36:23,881 --> 00:36:25,383
can I pray for you?

655
00:36:25,383 --> 00:36:27,885
No, no. Really, I’m good
. That’s not necessary.

656
00:36:27,885 --> 00:36:29,887
It’s, uh--
It’s what I do.

657
00:36:33,891 --> 00:36:36,727
Thank You, Lord,
for Brady.

658
00:36:36,978 --> 00:36:39,564
Thank You for
making him caretaker

659
00:36:39,564 --> 00:36:42,066
of these letters,

660
00:36:42,066 --> 00:36:43,568
and for his heart.

661
00:36:46,120 --> 00:36:50,124
Your plans
are always good.

662
00:36:50,124 --> 00:36:53,127
Lord, I believe
You have a plan

663
00:36:53,127 --> 00:36:56,130
and a purpose in this.

664
00:36:56,130 --> 00:36:58,132
Help Brady
discover that plan,

665
00:36:58,132 --> 00:37:02,220
because, Lord,
I know you’re about
to do something...

666
00:37:02,220 --> 00:37:04,222
wonderful.

667
00:37:04,222 --> 00:37:06,224
Something
more wonderful

668
00:37:06,224 --> 00:37:08,226
than we can
possibly imagine.

669
00:37:10,228 --> 00:37:12,730
In Jesus’ name
I pray.

670
00:37:14,732 --> 00:37:16,734
Amen.
Hmm.

671
00:37:18,736 --> 00:37:20,738
Well, sir,
how does it feel

672
00:37:20,738 --> 00:37:22,740
to be on a mission
for God?

673
00:37:24,242 --> 00:37:26,744
[Chuckles]

674
00:37:27,245 --> 00:37:28,746
Heh-heh.

675
00:37:30,748 --> 00:37:32,250
Perfect.

676
00:37:58,526 --> 00:38:00,528
Shouldn’t you be
in school?

677
00:38:00,528 --> 00:38:04,031
No. My mom
thought I should
take it easy today.

678
00:38:04,031 --> 00:38:06,033
Is your mom home?

679
00:38:06,033 --> 00:38:08,402
No. At work.
Oh.

680
00:38:08,703 --> 00:38:10,788
But my Granna’s here.

681
00:38:10,788 --> 00:38:12,740
Granna!

682
00:38:14,241 --> 00:38:15,743
[Sighs]

683
00:38:15,743 --> 00:38:18,245
I’m sorry about
your shoes yesterday.

684
00:38:18,245 --> 00:38:19,246
Ah, it’s all right.

685
00:38:19,246 --> 00:38:21,248
Cujo down the street
pretty much ruined them

686
00:38:21,248 --> 00:38:22,667
before you
got to them, so...

687
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:24,585
You mean Rooster?

688
00:38:24,585 --> 00:38:26,587
Oh, he’s a big
teddy bear.

689
00:38:26,587 --> 00:38:28,589
You just gotta know
what he likes.

690
00:38:29,090 --> 00:38:31,592
Rooster?
Rooster, the dog.

691
00:38:31,592 --> 00:38:33,511
What is it, honey?

692
00:38:33,511 --> 00:38:35,062
Oh, hello.

693
00:38:35,062 --> 00:38:36,597
Brady McDaniels.

694
00:38:36,597 --> 00:38:38,599
I’m filling in
for Mr. Finley.
Oh, yes.

695
00:38:38,599 --> 00:38:42,153
And, uh, this is from
down the street. Uh...

696
00:38:42,153 --> 00:38:44,155
[Laughs]
That would be Linda Baker.

697
00:38:44,155 --> 00:38:46,657
She’s such a dear.
Eight months pregnant,

698
00:38:47,158 --> 00:38:48,659
and her soldier
husband’s away,

699
00:38:48,659 --> 00:38:50,444
and still she’s thinking
about other people.

700
00:38:50,661 --> 00:38:53,247
Honey, it’s time for you
to come in now.

701
00:38:53,247 --> 00:38:54,749
Can I wait for Sam?

702
00:38:54,749 --> 00:38:57,034
She’s gonna be home
from school any minute.

703
00:38:57,251 --> 00:38:59,337
.
Well, all right,
but just don’t overdo it

704
00:38:59,337 --> 00:39:00,838
Nice to meet you,
young man.

705
00:39:00,838 --> 00:39:02,840
Likewise.

706
00:39:02,840 --> 00:39:03,841
Uh...

707
00:39:03,841 --> 00:39:05,343
[Bus approaches]

708
00:39:05,843 --> 00:39:07,345
Here you go.
Oh.

709
00:39:07,345 --> 00:39:08,846
Here you go.

710
00:39:11,932 --> 00:39:13,017
Excuse me!

711
00:39:13,517 --> 00:39:14,518
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Where’s the fire?

712
00:39:15,019 --> 00:39:16,637
Tell me everything.

713
00:39:16,637 --> 00:39:19,140
Okay. So, Alex and I
had to write 500 times,

714
00:39:19,140 --> 00:39:20,641
"I will not fight."

715
00:39:20,641 --> 00:39:22,643
But Alex had to write
another 500 times,

716
00:39:22,643 --> 00:39:24,145
"I will not make fun
of people."

717
00:39:24,145 --> 00:39:26,147
[Both laugh]

718
00:39:26,147 --> 00:39:28,649
People are always
gonna make fun of me.

719
00:39:30,651 --> 00:39:33,654
Come on. I think I know
something that could help.

720
00:39:33,654 --> 00:39:35,156
Okay.

721
00:39:41,879 --> 00:39:43,881
Every day?

722
00:39:43,881 --> 00:39:46,717
You’ve got to drink
that stuff every day?

723
00:39:47,001 --> 00:39:48,586
Barf!

724
00:39:50,087 --> 00:39:52,089
Barf yourself,
Mr. Doherty.

725
00:39:52,089 --> 00:39:55,092
The doctor says
drink it, I drink it.

726
00:39:55,092 --> 00:39:57,094
Like it or not.

727
00:39:59,930 --> 00:40:01,432
[Whispering]
That explains it.

728
00:40:01,932 --> 00:40:03,434
Explains what?

729
00:40:03,434 --> 00:40:04,902
I’d be grouchy, too...

730
00:40:05,269 --> 00:40:08,355
if I had to drink that.

731
00:40:08,355 --> 00:40:12,359
Grandpa,
we need your help.

732
00:40:12,359 --> 00:40:15,162
Can’t. I’m busy.

733
00:40:15,362 --> 00:40:17,948
Grandpa, please?

734
00:40:17,948 --> 00:40:20,367
It’s big-time.

735
00:40:22,253 --> 00:40:24,538
Hmm. Okay.
Make it quick.

736
00:40:30,127 --> 00:40:34,131
So, you say they’re
picking on you at school.

737
00:40:34,131 --> 00:40:37,635
Well, one kid, really.
Alex.

738
00:40:37,635 --> 00:40:39,136
Oh.

739
00:40:39,637 --> 00:40:41,138
Don’t let it
bother you.

740
00:40:41,639 --> 00:40:43,140
They’re jealous,
that’s all.

741
00:40:43,641 --> 00:40:44,558
Jealous?

742
00:40:44,859 --> 00:40:46,444
Because all my hair
fell out?

743
00:40:46,444 --> 00:40:48,779
And my eyebrows
are almost gone?

744
00:40:49,029 --> 00:40:51,115
No.

745
00:40:51,115 --> 00:40:54,618
They’re jealous because
you’ve been chosen

746
00:40:54,618 --> 00:40:58,122
for the role
of your lifetime.

747
00:40:58,122 --> 00:41:00,958
You’ve been
handpicked by God.

748
00:41:03,794 --> 00:41:04,795
You don’t believe me?

749
00:41:06,297 --> 00:41:10,301
Well, maybe we’d better
ask Baron Dedushka.

750
00:41:10,301 --> 00:41:11,719
Dedushka?

751
00:41:12,086 --> 00:41:14,171
Are you in there?

752
00:41:16,056 --> 00:41:17,057
Dedushka?

753
00:41:19,560 --> 00:41:21,345
Dedushka!

754
00:41:21,595 --> 00:41:25,900
!
Good news, Dedushka--he’s here

755
00:41:25,900 --> 00:41:27,902
Ooh-la-la!

756
00:41:27,902 --> 00:41:29,236
Ooh-la-la!
Ooh-la-la-la!

757
00:41:29,487 --> 00:41:30,571
[Both laughing]

758
00:41:30,571 --> 00:41:33,574
Ooh-la-la! Ooh-la-la!
Ooh-la--

759
00:41:33,574 --> 00:41:35,075
[Laughing]

760
00:41:35,576 --> 00:41:37,077
You’re him!

761
00:41:37,077 --> 00:41:40,331
You must be
the famous Tyler.

762
00:41:40,531 --> 00:41:42,082
Why am I
the famous one?

763
00:41:42,449 --> 00:41:44,535
Because God has chosen you--

764
00:41:44,535 --> 00:41:48,038
the strongest, the wisest,
the smartest--

765
00:41:48,038 --> 00:41:50,007
to receive the honor.

766
00:41:50,457 --> 00:41:53,844
Honor? Like a gold star
at school, Mr. Perryfield?

767
00:41:54,044 --> 00:41:57,131
No, not Perryfield.
Dedushka.

768
00:41:57,131 --> 00:41:59,633
And Dedushka mean
not that kind of honor.

769
00:41:59,633 --> 00:42:03,103
.
The honor of being chosen
as one of God’s warriors

770
00:42:03,470 --> 00:42:05,556
Wow!

771
00:42:05,556 --> 00:42:07,391
I want to be a warrior.

772
00:42:07,641 --> 00:42:09,727
Oh, well...

773
00:42:09,727 --> 00:42:12,730
Samantha, I talked
to the principal.

774
00:42:12,730 --> 00:42:14,732
He said you need
a little less warrior

775
00:42:14,732 --> 00:42:17,618
and a little more...
peacemaker.

776
00:42:17,902 --> 00:42:20,487
Samantha
the peacemaker.

777
00:42:22,489 --> 00:42:23,991
It doesn’t sound
as good as warrior,

778
00:42:23,991 --> 00:42:25,492
but I’ll give it
a try.

779
00:42:25,492 --> 00:42:27,995
PERRYFIELD: Okay, good.
Now, where was I?

780
00:42:27,995 --> 00:42:29,797
I’m a warrior.

781
00:42:30,047 --> 00:42:31,632
Ah, yes,
you are God’s warrior,

782
00:42:31,632 --> 00:42:34,134
which means you can
ride forth victoriously

783
00:42:34,134 --> 00:42:37,504
in truth, humility,
and righteousness.

784
00:42:37,805 --> 00:42:41,892
Dedushka is honored
to know you.

785
00:42:43,894 --> 00:42:45,813
Now, come here, Tyler.

786
00:42:49,316 --> 00:42:50,818
Tyler, come here.

787
00:42:52,820 --> 00:42:54,822
Even though you’re sick,

788
00:42:54,822 --> 00:42:58,275
when people see how
strong and brave you are,

789
00:42:58,692 --> 00:43:02,279
why, it makes them take
a look at their own lives.

790
00:43:02,696 --> 00:43:05,282
And so, maybe that’s
why they make fun of you

791
00:43:05,282 --> 00:43:07,284
like Alex.

792
00:43:07,284 --> 00:43:09,253
But, Tyler, there is
a glorious truth.

793
00:43:09,587 --> 00:43:11,672
God is truth.

794
00:43:11,672 --> 00:43:13,507
And it’s your job,
Tyler,

795
00:43:13,757 --> 00:43:15,843
to point them
toward Him.

796
00:43:15,843 --> 00:43:17,294
And if they
turn to Him,

797
00:43:17,711 --> 00:43:20,297
they find the truth.

798
00:43:20,798 --> 00:43:24,301
Wouldn’t that be
a wonderful victory?

799
00:43:27,304 --> 00:43:30,107
Tyler,
do you understand?

800
00:43:30,608 --> 00:43:32,610
I think so.

801
00:43:33,611 --> 00:43:35,112
Grandpa...

802
00:43:35,529 --> 00:43:37,114
I don’t.

803
00:43:37,114 --> 00:43:38,115
Ah.

804
00:43:39,617 --> 00:43:42,236
I don’t feel so brave
because of...

805
00:43:44,238 --> 00:43:45,205
PERRYFIELD: Ah.

806
00:43:46,657 --> 00:43:48,158
[Sighs]

807
00:43:52,162 --> 00:43:54,164
I have an idea.

808
00:44:05,092 --> 00:44:07,094
SAM: Grandpa, can I see?

809
00:44:07,094 --> 00:44:09,096
Samantha, be still.

810
00:44:09,096 --> 00:44:12,349
Now, you hold still.
We’re almost done.

811
00:44:12,650 --> 00:44:14,234
All right.

812
00:44:18,739 --> 00:44:20,240
SAM: Grandpa,
can I see?

813
00:44:20,240 --> 00:44:22,526
Samantha, be patient.

814
00:44:23,777 --> 00:44:26,163
How do you feel?
They feel great.

815
00:44:26,163 --> 00:44:29,166
Good. Now raise them up.
Right.

816
00:44:29,166 --> 00:44:30,668
Now your right one.

817
00:44:30,668 --> 00:44:33,671
[Laughing]
Your left one.

818
00:44:33,671 --> 00:44:35,039
Finished!

819
00:44:35,339 --> 00:44:36,423
We’re done.

820
00:44:36,423 --> 00:44:37,925
Yes!
All right!

821
00:44:37,925 --> 00:44:39,927
Just a moment.

822
00:44:39,927 --> 00:44:41,762
Fantastic!

823
00:44:43,597 --> 00:44:44,598
How are they?

824
00:44:44,598 --> 00:44:46,100
They’re awesome!

825
00:44:46,100 --> 00:44:47,601
They’re fantastic!

826
00:44:48,018 --> 00:44:49,603
They’re awesomely
fantastic.

827
00:44:49,603 --> 00:44:50,888
[Laughs]

828
00:44:51,055 --> 00:44:52,139
I want to see!
I want to see!

829
00:44:52,139 --> 00:44:53,640
Here you go.

830
00:44:56,143 --> 00:44:57,644
Cool.

831
00:44:57,644 --> 00:45:00,147
Awesome.
[Laughs]

832
00:45:00,147 --> 00:45:01,148
All right.

833
00:45:01,648 --> 00:45:03,650
Now, will you
get out of here?

834
00:45:03,650 --> 00:45:05,652
Dedushka is tired.

835
00:45:05,652 --> 00:45:07,654
Thanks, Grandpa.
All right.

836
00:45:07,654 --> 00:45:09,156
Ohh.

837
00:45:14,378 --> 00:45:16,880
Oh, you’re home early.
Yep.

838
00:45:16,880 --> 00:45:18,882
Made your favorite.

839
00:45:18,882 --> 00:45:20,384
That’s Ty’s favorite.

840
00:45:20,384 --> 00:45:22,386
Oh.

841
00:45:22,386 --> 00:45:23,887
Well, now,
don’t tell me.

842
00:45:23,887 --> 00:45:25,389
Don’t tell me.
Let me guess.

843
00:45:25,389 --> 00:45:27,391
Yours is...
carrot cake.

844
00:45:27,391 --> 00:45:28,892
Mm-mm.

845
00:45:28,892 --> 00:45:30,894
Uh, marble?
Nope.

846
00:45:30,894 --> 00:45:32,396
Black Forest.
No.

847
00:45:32,396 --> 00:45:33,647
Oh, gosh.

848
00:45:33,847 --> 00:45:35,432
Premature senility.

849
00:45:35,432 --> 00:45:37,317
I’ve always been
afraid of it.

850
00:45:37,317 --> 00:45:39,820
It’s okay. Forget it.
It’s all good.

851
00:45:39,820 --> 00:45:41,321
Ah-ah-ah-ah.
Come here.

852
00:45:41,321 --> 00:45:43,824
Sit down. Stir.

853
00:45:50,330 --> 00:45:52,332
Why don’t you tell me
what’s on your mind?

854
00:45:53,834 --> 00:45:55,335
Nothing.

855
00:45:57,838 --> 00:46:00,340
Everything.

856
00:46:00,340 --> 00:46:02,843
Well, that about
covers it.

857
00:46:02,843 --> 00:46:04,845
I just feel weird,
you know?

858
00:46:04,845 --> 00:46:06,847
About Ty and what
he’s going through.

859
00:46:07,347 --> 00:46:09,349
All the attention
he gets.

860
00:46:09,349 --> 00:46:13,187
I mean, I know that sounds
totally stupid and selfish.

861
00:46:13,470 --> 00:46:17,057
I just hate
that he’s sick.

862
00:46:17,558 --> 00:46:21,361
Oh, sweetheart, we all
hate that he’s sick.

863
00:46:21,862 --> 00:46:23,363
Sometimes I think
it’s worse for us

864
00:46:23,363 --> 00:46:25,365
than it is for him.

865
00:46:25,365 --> 00:46:27,201
So go easy on yourself.

866
00:46:27,451 --> 00:46:29,036
I just want normal,
Granna.

867
00:46:29,036 --> 00:46:30,537
I mean, do you know
how many times

868
00:46:30,537 --> 00:46:33,040
I’ve asked for Mom just 
to take me to get my license?

869
00:46:33,040 --> 00:46:34,041
No.

870
00:46:34,041 --> 00:46:35,492
Well, you can’t count
that high.

871
00:46:36,043 --> 00:46:37,544
Oh, Ben.

872
00:46:37,544 --> 00:46:39,546
We can’t do anything
because we don’t
have any money

873
00:46:40,047 --> 00:46:41,915
and Tyler’s always sick
or he’s in the hospital.

874
00:46:42,249 --> 00:46:44,835
Well, shall we accept
good from God

875
00:46:44,835 --> 00:46:45,836
and not trouble?

876
00:46:46,253 --> 00:46:48,839
.
It just seems like
all we’re getting is trouble

877
00:46:49,339 --> 00:46:51,842
MADDY: Hey. Ben, did you
take the trash to the curb?

878
00:46:51,842 --> 00:46:53,844
Honey, we were
talking here.

879
00:46:53,844 --> 00:46:55,345
Well, that’s not
gonna get the trash
to the curb.

880
00:46:55,345 --> 00:46:56,847
Talking doesn’t even
matter to her anymore.

881
00:46:56,847 --> 00:46:58,348
All she does
is bark orders.

882
00:46:58,348 --> 00:47:00,350
Ben, don’t talk to me
like that.

883
00:47:00,851 --> 00:47:02,352
Okay, then, fine. I’ll jus
t stop talking altogether.

884
00:47:02,352 --> 00:47:03,854
Because I’m practically
invisible anyways.

885
00:47:03,854 --> 00:47:05,355
Benjamin!

886
00:47:05,355 --> 00:47:06,857
I’m sick of all this.
I just wish--

887
00:47:06,857 --> 00:47:08,192
It’s all about Tyler.

888
00:47:08,492 --> 00:47:10,077
Benjamin,
I am warning you--

889
00:47:10,077 --> 00:47:11,745
All of our time,
all of our money,
everything.

890
00:47:11,745 --> 00:47:14,248
I just--
I just hate him!

891
00:47:14,248 --> 00:47:15,532
[Clatter]

892
00:47:16,867 --> 00:47:17,918
Tyler, wait!

893
00:47:19,920 --> 00:47:21,922
Maddy, let Ben
handle this, honey.

894
00:47:21,922 --> 00:47:23,423
[Sighs]

895
00:47:23,423 --> 00:47:25,425
Come over here
and sit down.

896
00:47:25,425 --> 00:47:27,427
Ohh.
Come on, sweetheart.

897
00:47:28,929 --> 00:47:30,430
I can’t do this.

898
00:47:30,430 --> 00:47:32,933
Oh, sweetie.
Yes, you can.

899
00:47:32,933 --> 00:47:35,385
[Sighs]
He didn’t mean it.

900
00:47:37,354 --> 00:47:39,356
Were those eyebrows?

901
00:47:39,356 --> 00:47:41,358
[Laughs]
Yes! They were.

902
00:47:41,358 --> 00:47:43,310
[Both laughing]

903
00:47:53,320 --> 00:47:55,322
Go away, or I’ll jump.

904
00:47:55,322 --> 00:47:57,824
[Sighs]
No, you won’t.

905
00:47:57,824 --> 00:48:00,327
How do you know?

906
00:48:00,327 --> 00:48:02,329
Well, because
it took me a week

907
00:48:02,329 --> 00:48:04,331
to get you out here
in the first place.

908
00:48:09,336 --> 00:48:10,837
Come on, sit.

909
00:48:22,933 --> 00:48:24,434
Look...

910
00:48:24,434 --> 00:48:26,436
I just wanted to say
that I’m sorry

911
00:48:26,436 --> 00:48:28,438
and that I didn’t mean
any of those things

912
00:48:28,438 --> 00:48:30,440
that I said back there.

913
00:48:33,944 --> 00:48:36,947
What do you see
when you look at me?

914
00:48:36,947 --> 00:48:38,949
Ty, don’t be like that.

915
00:48:38,949 --> 00:48:39,950
I’m serious.

916
00:48:40,367 --> 00:48:43,453
I know you’re mad at me
because I’m sick.

917
00:48:43,453 --> 00:48:46,456
Ty, I’m not mad at you
because you’re sick.

918
00:48:46,456 --> 00:48:48,342
And I don’t hate you.

919
00:48:48,675 --> 00:48:50,761
I guess I just miss you.

920
00:48:52,262 --> 00:48:53,764
I miss all
the fun times we had,

921
00:48:53,764 --> 00:48:56,266
and I guess I’m just
afraid that--

922
00:48:56,266 --> 00:48:59,770
that we might not have
any of those ever again.

923
00:49:12,316 --> 00:49:13,700
You’re such a dweeb.

924
00:49:13,951 --> 00:49:15,535
You’re such a toad.

925
00:49:15,535 --> 00:49:17,037
[Chuckles]

926
00:49:17,037 --> 00:49:19,406
I want you to write
a letter to God.

927
00:49:19,706 --> 00:49:21,792
I want you to tell Him
how you feel.

928
00:49:21,792 --> 00:49:24,294
I’m sure that He can
help you and Mom.

929
00:49:26,797 --> 00:49:28,799
Not to sound mean, but...

930
00:49:28,799 --> 00:49:31,218
Ty, that’s really lame.

931
00:49:31,501 --> 00:49:33,086
It’s not lame.

932
00:49:33,086 --> 00:49:35,589
It’s my favorite way
to talk to God.

933
00:49:35,589 --> 00:49:38,558
It’s like texting
your best friend.

934
00:49:40,010 --> 00:49:41,511
You’re right.

935
00:49:41,511 --> 00:49:43,513
Okay.
All right.

936
00:49:43,513 --> 00:49:45,515
Okay.

937
00:49:45,515 --> 00:49:47,017
[Sighs]

938
00:49:49,519 --> 00:49:50,354
Here’s your pad.

939
00:49:50,654 --> 00:49:52,239
All right.

940
00:49:54,241 --> 00:49:56,243
I’m a warrior, you know.

941
00:49:56,243 --> 00:49:58,195
Heh. A warrior, huh?

942
00:49:58,612 --> 00:50:00,697
Well, I think
you’re gonna have to be,
with those eyebrows.

943
00:50:02,699 --> 00:50:04,034
[Laughs]

944
00:50:09,923 --> 00:50:12,426
[Sighs] So, uh...

945
00:50:12,426 --> 00:50:13,927
is Sam your girlfriend?

946
00:50:14,428 --> 00:50:16,430
Yuck! No way!

947
00:50:16,430 --> 00:50:18,432
Okay. Sorry I asked.

948
00:50:18,432 --> 00:50:20,934
Well, she’s my best--
like a boy--kind of friend.

949
00:50:21,435 --> 00:50:23,937
Hmm, right.
Enough said.

950
00:50:25,939 --> 00:50:27,441
You have any kids?

951
00:50:28,942 --> 00:50:32,446
[Sighs]
I have a boy.

952
00:50:32,446 --> 00:50:36,450
Uh...a little bit
younger than you.

953
00:50:36,450 --> 00:50:38,952
He lives with his mom,
though, so I don’t--

954
00:50:39,453 --> 00:50:40,954
I don’t see him much.

955
00:50:40,954 --> 00:50:42,956
Oh. That’s too bad.

956
00:50:42,956 --> 00:50:44,458
Yeah.

957
00:50:44,958 --> 00:50:45,959
Well...

958
00:50:49,413 --> 00:50:50,914
[Grunts]

959
00:50:53,417 --> 00:50:54,918
Aw, cool.

960
00:50:54,918 --> 00:50:56,920
Like that?
Yeah.

961
00:51:02,392 --> 00:51:03,393
Nice.

962
00:51:06,897 --> 00:51:08,815
Heh. Hey, maybe you can
show me that move.

963
00:51:12,769 --> 00:51:14,271
Okay, come on.

964
00:51:16,573 --> 00:51:19,443
Nice! Not bad.

965
00:51:20,827 --> 00:51:23,663
So...are you on a team?

966
00:51:23,914 --> 00:51:25,499
Yeah.

967
00:51:25,499 --> 00:51:27,501
I haven’t played
since I got sick.

968
00:51:27,501 --> 00:51:28,785
I want to, though.

969
00:51:29,035 --> 00:51:30,120
Yeah.

970
00:51:32,839 --> 00:51:35,675
Hey. Buddy,
go wash up for dinner.

971
00:51:35,926 --> 00:51:37,511
Okay.
Hi.

972
00:51:39,296 --> 00:51:40,380
Thanks for the game.

973
00:51:40,380 --> 00:51:43,884
You got it, tiger.
Hey! Be quick!

974
00:51:43,884 --> 00:51:44,885
Heh.

975
00:51:45,385 --> 00:51:46,386
Uh, Brady.

976
00:51:46,386 --> 00:51:47,888
I’m Madelyn Doherty.

977
00:51:47,888 --> 00:51:49,890
But everyone
calls me Maddy.

978
00:51:53,860 --> 00:51:56,947
Anyway, it’s, uh--

979
00:51:56,947 --> 00:51:58,448
it’s not serious, is it?

980
00:51:58,448 --> 00:51:59,950
I mean, he’s gonna
be okay, right?

981
00:52:00,317 --> 00:52:02,402
We hope so.

982
00:52:02,402 --> 00:52:04,404
Good.
Yeah.

983
00:52:06,156 --> 00:52:08,625
He’s a good kid.
Thank you.

984
00:52:14,714 --> 00:52:16,216
Um, Brady?

985
00:52:16,216 --> 00:52:17,667
Your...bag.

986
00:52:17,667 --> 00:52:19,719
Oh. Heh! Okay.

987
00:52:19,719 --> 00:52:21,721
Gonna need that.
Yeah.

988
00:52:21,721 --> 00:52:23,590
Whoops.

989
00:52:23,890 --> 00:52:26,893
Um, my--my mail?

990
00:52:27,227 --> 00:52:28,311
Oh. Right.

991
00:52:28,311 --> 00:52:30,313
Yes. Uh...

992
00:52:31,815 --> 00:52:34,100
Here. Sorry.
[Laughs]

993
00:52:34,317 --> 00:52:35,902
It’s mostly bills
anyway.

994
00:52:35,902 --> 00:52:37,404
Yeah. "Urgent".

995
00:52:37,404 --> 00:52:39,406
[Telephone rings]
Oh. More bills.

996
00:52:39,406 --> 00:52:40,357
[Laughs]

997
00:52:40,774 --> 00:52:42,325
[Ring]

998
00:52:42,325 --> 00:52:43,860
Um, hey, listen,

999
00:52:43,860 --> 00:52:47,364
thank you for taking
some time with Tyler.

1000
00:52:47,364 --> 00:52:49,866
I really
appreciate that.

1001
00:52:49,866 --> 00:52:51,868
BEN: Mom! Phone!

1002
00:52:51,868 --> 00:52:53,203
I’m coming!

1003
00:52:53,453 --> 00:52:55,038
Okay. We’ll see you.

1004
00:52:55,038 --> 00:52:56,540
Bye-bye.
Bye.

1005
00:53:08,468 --> 00:53:10,053
Whew!

1006
00:53:10,053 --> 00:53:11,555
Hey, buddy.
Hi, Mom.

1007
00:53:12,055 --> 00:53:13,056
Whatcha doin’?

1008
00:53:13,056 --> 00:53:15,058
I’m writing
a letter to Alex.

1009
00:53:15,058 --> 00:53:17,561
Alex? From school?

1010
00:53:17,561 --> 00:53:19,062
Yeah.

1011
00:53:19,062 --> 00:53:20,897
Hmm.

1012
00:53:21,114 --> 00:53:23,700
You see, I just
want him to know

1013
00:53:23,700 --> 00:53:25,702
that I’m not mad
at him,

1014
00:53:25,702 --> 00:53:28,038
and that I can
understand why
he makes fun of me.

1015
00:53:29,906 --> 00:53:33,293
Mr. Perryfield said
that I’m God’s warrior,

1016
00:53:33,293 --> 00:53:35,745
and that I can make him
feel things that...

1017
00:53:36,129 --> 00:53:38,215
he doesn’t want to feel.

1018
00:53:38,215 --> 00:53:39,583
But that’s good.

1019
00:53:39,833 --> 00:53:41,418
Because maybe...

1020
00:53:41,418 --> 00:53:43,720
he’ll turn to God
for the answers.

1021
00:53:47,507 --> 00:53:50,510
Well, Mr. Perryfield
is a very smart man.

1022
00:53:52,512 --> 00:53:54,981
So...what’s up?

1023
00:53:55,398 --> 00:53:57,984
Well, sweetheart...

1024
00:53:57,984 --> 00:54:02,989
um, it’s time to go back
and finish your medicine.

1025
00:54:08,745 --> 00:54:10,196
Really?

1026
00:54:10,614 --> 00:54:12,198
Yeah, really.

1027
00:54:16,753 --> 00:54:19,039
Okay.

1028
00:54:19,289 --> 00:54:20,874
Okay.

1029
00:55:22,902 --> 00:55:23,903
[Sighs]

1030
00:55:24,404 --> 00:55:25,405
Ohh.

1031
00:55:27,357 --> 00:55:29,409
POLICE RADIO:
Roger. Unit 72 responding.

1032
00:55:29,409 --> 00:55:31,194
D.U.I. suspect.

1033
00:55:31,194 --> 00:55:33,580
We have a minor boy
in the back seat.

1034
00:55:34,080 --> 00:55:35,949
D.U.I. suspect
being booked.
